I"ş<p><a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/attractors-and-repellors-have-opposite-behaviors-in-dynamical-systems">Attractors and repellors</a> can be expressed as <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/sum-of-elements-represents-their-set-in-hyperdimensional-computing">sets</a>. They are sets of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">states</a> in which a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/continuous-state-dynamical-systems-share-a-common-structure">dynamical system</a> either always finds itself or never does so after an infinite number of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/tense-logic-formalizes-time">steps</a> when starting off from a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/bifurcations-segment-space-of-dynamical-systems-in-basins">basin</a>. The â€œborderâ€ or â€œmembraneâ€ of such a set can be described as <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/hopfield-networks-are-energy-based-memory-models">energy barriers</a>.</p>
